##DESCRIPTION
##DIFFICULTY('easy')
##  Evaluate simple expressions involving logs
##ENDDESCRIPTION
## DBsubject(Algebra)
## DBchapter(Exponential and logarithmic expressions and functions)
## DBsection(Logarithmic functions)
## Institution(Univeristy of Utah)
## Author(Utah ww group)
## MLT(EvalByLogRules)
## Level(4)
## TitleText1('Calculus I')
## AuthorText1('Jerrold Marsden and Alan Weinstein')
## EditionText1('2')
## Section1('.')
## Problem1('')
## KEYWORDS('calculus')

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$a1 = random(2,9,1);
$b1 = random(2,15,1);
$c1 = random(2,3,1);
$d1 = random(3,5,1);
$e1 = $c1**$d1;
$f1 = random(2,9,1);
$g1 = random(2,15,1);
$h1 = random(4,5,1);
$i1 = random(3,5,1);
$j1 = $h1**$i1;

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
You should be able to do the first two problems without using a
calculator.  Use the basic definitions of logarithms and exponentials.
If you see a base 3 logarithm, for example, compute the first few
powers of 3, and see how they relate to the number of which you are
taking the logarithm.

$PAR

Evaluate the following expressions.
$PAR
(a) \( \log_ { $c1 } \left ( \frac {1} { $e1 }\right ) = \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT

$ans = -$d1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
(b) \( \log_ { $a1 } 1 = \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT

$ans = 0;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
(c) \( \log_ { $h1 } \sqrt { $j1 } = \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT

$ans = $i1/2;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
(d) \( $f1 ^ { \log_ {$f1 } $g1 } = \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT

$ans = $g1;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));


ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.;
